TY  - JOUR
T1  - Finding the n Most Vital Links in Flow Networks
AU  - Ratliff, H. Donald
AU  - Sicilia, G. Thomas
AU  - Lubore, S. H.
Y1  - 1975/01/01
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.21.5.531
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.21.5.531
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 531
EP  - 539
VL  - 21
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The n most vital links of a flow network are defined as those n arcs whose simultaneous removal from the network causes the greatest decrease in the throughput capability of the remaining system between a specified pair of nodes. These n arcs are shown to be the n largest capacity arcs in a particular cut. A solution procedure is developed which involves sequentially modifying the network so as to make this cut eventually become the cut with smallest capacity. An algorithm with computational results is presented.
AB  - The n most vital links of a flow network are defined as those n arcs whose simultaneous removal from the network causes the greatest decrease in the throughput capability of the remaining system between a specified pair of nodes. These n arcs are shown to be the n largest capacity arcs in a particular cut. A solution procedure is developed which involves sequentially modifying the network so as to make this cut eventually become the cut with smallest capacity. An algorithm with computational results is presented.
